const Q_BIOLOGY_2020_MODEL_II=[{"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following does not illustrate adaptation to the environment? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> Colour changes by chameleon </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> Streamline shape of fishes </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Light bones in birds </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Development of big muscles by a weight lifter </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Adaptation to the environment refers to the process by which an organism becomes better suited to its habitat. This is usually a result of evolution and takes place over many generations. The development of big muscles by a weight lifter is not an adaptation to the environment. It is a physiological change in response to exercise and does not involve genetic changes that can be passed on to the next generation.</div>", "topic": "ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL : ADAPTIVE COLOURATION AND ITS FUNCTIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The changing of colour by a chameleon to that of the environment is an example of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adaptive radiation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> protective coloration </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">courtship display </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> display of body colour </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The changing of colour by a chameleon to match its environment is an example of protective coloration. This is a type of camouflage that allows the chameleon to blend in with its surroundings and avoid detection by predators. Adaptive radiation refers to the process by which species evolve from a single ancestral species into a wide array of species to fit a number of diverse habitats. Courtship display is a set of display behaviours in which an animal attempts to attract a mate and signal their readiness to copulate. Display of body colour is a general term that could refer to a number of different phenomena, not necessarily related to camouflage.</div>", "topic": "ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL : ADAPTIVE COLOURATION AND ITS FUNCTIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The division of labour in social insects is an example of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">structural adaptation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">physiological adaptation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">commensalism </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">behavioural adaptation </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The division of labour in social insects is an example of behavioural adaptation. This refers to changes in an organism's behaviour that help it survive and reproduce in its environment. Structural adaptation refers to physical changes in an organism that help it survive in its environment. Physiological adaptation refers to changes in an organism's internal functions that help it survive in its environment. Commensalism is a type of symbiotic relationship where one organism benefits and the other is not significantly harmed or helped.</div>", "topic": "ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Increasing specialization of structure and function among animals of the same class and order for survival in new and different environments is called </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adaptive radiation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">phylogeny </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">homology </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">analogy </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Increasing specialization of structure and function among animals of the same class and order for survival in new and different environments is called adaptive radiation. This is a process in evolution where an organism diversifies rapidly from an ancestral species into a multitude of new forms, particularly when a change in the environment makes new resources available, creates new challenges, or opens new environmental niches. Phylogeny refers to the evolutionary history and relationships among or within groups of organisms. Homology refers to similarity in sequence of a protein or nucleic acid or in the structure of an organ that reflects common ancestry. Analogy refers to the similarity of function and superficial resemblance of structures that have different origins.</div>", "topic": "EVOLUTION : THEORIES OF EVOLUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When protein are broken down they provide </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oxygen </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">carbohydrate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">energy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">amino-acid </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When proteins are broken down, they provide amino acids. Proteins are made up of amino acids and when they are digested or broken down, amino acids are left. These are used to build and repair tissues among other things.</div>", "topic": "NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Autotropic nutrition may be defined in terms of food obtained </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">from other organisms in exchange for some products. </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by the breakdown of complex substances </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by an organism utilizing its own store of energy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by synthesizing simple substances using energy from an external source </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Autotrophic nutrition is defined as the process by which organisms synthesize their own food using simple substances like carbon dioxide and water, and energy from an external source, usually sunlight, through a process called photosynthesis. Autotrophs, such as plants, algae, and some bacteria, are capable of converting light energy, usually from the sun, into chemical energy in the form of glucose.</div>", "topic": "NUTRITION : MODES OF NUTRITION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The source of energy required by plants during food production is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Photosynthesis </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Chlorophyll </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sunlight </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Microorganisms </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The source of energy required by plants during food production, or photosynthesis, is sunlight. Photosynthesis is the process by which green plants and some other organisms use sunlight to synthesize foods with the help of chlorophyll pigments. During this process, light energy is converted into chemical energy in the form of glucose, which can be used by the plant for growth and development.</div>", "topic": "NUTRITION : PHOTOSYNTHESIS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One major difference between plant and animals nutrition is the ability of plants to synthesize </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Food for plants and animals </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Water for plants </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Water for animals </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Food for plants only. </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The major difference between plant and animal nutrition is that plants can synthesize their own food through a process called photosynthesis. Animals, on the other hand, cannot synthesize their own food and must obtain it by eating plants or other animals. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Food for plants and animals .'</div>", "topic": "NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which part of the human digestive system is responsible for most nutrient absorption?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Stomach</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Small intestine</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Large intestine</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Oesophagus</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The small intestine is where most nutrient absorption occurs. Its lining contains villi and microvilli, which greatly increase the surface area for absorption of nutrients into the bloodstream. The stomach mainly breaks down food, the large intestine absorbs water and some minerals, and the oesophagus only transports food to the stomach.</div>", "topic": "TRANSPORT : MAMMALIAN CIRCULATORY SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Active transport differs from diffusion in that active transport </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is a very fast process </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">allows the movement of substances against concentration gradient </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">takes place in both light and dark reaction of photosynthesis </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">occurs in both plant and animal tissues. </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Active transport is a process that moves molecules into or out of a cell from a region of lower concentration to a region of higher concentration. This process requires energy because it is moving substances against the concentration gradient. Therefore, the correct answer is 'allows the movement of substances against concentration gradient.'</div>", "topic": "TRANSPORT : MATERIALS FOR TRANSPORTATION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The reason why the flow of blood through the capillaries is very slow is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">because the walls of capillaries are very thin </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to avoid high blood pressure </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to ensure that the individual does not get dizzy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to allow adequate time for exchange of materials. </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The flow of blood through the capillaries is very slow to allow adequate time for exchange of materials. Capillaries are the smallest blood vessels where the exchange of oxygen, carbon dioxide, nutrients, and waste materials occurs between the blood and the body's cells. The slow flow rate allows for maximum diffusion of these substances.</div>", "topic": "TRANSPORT : MAMMALIAN CIRCULATORY SYSTEM"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Scientists who study genetics are known as </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">genealogist </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">geneticist </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mendalists </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">genescientists </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Scientists who study genetics are known as geneticists. Genetics is the study of genes, genetic variation, and heredity in organisms. A geneticist is a biologist who studies these processes. The other terms do not refer to scientists who study genetics.</div>", "topic": "HEREDITY : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following scientists did not contribute to the development of genetics? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Wilhem Johannsen </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Felix Dujardin </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thomas Morgan </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Gregor Mendel </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Felix Dujardin did not contribute to the development of genetics. Wilhelm Johannsen, Thomas Morgan, and Gregor Mendel are all notable figures in the field of genetics. Johannsen coined the term 'gene', Morgan worked on chromosome theory of inheritance, and Mendel is known as the father of modern genetics for his work on pea plants.</div>", "topic": "HEREDITY : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following terms is associated with natural selections? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adaptive radiation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Differential reproduction </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Population variability </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Survival of the fittest </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term 'Survival of the fittest' is associated with natural selection. Natural selection is a process where organisms better adapted to their environment tend to survive and produce more offspring. The concept is often summarized as 'Survival of the fittest', a term coined by Herbert Spencer after reading Charles Darwin's 'On the Origin of Species'.</div>", "topic": "EVOLUTION : THEORIES OF EVOLUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The part of the male reproductive organ where sperm cells are produced is called </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">epididymis </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">penis </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seminal vesicle </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seminiferous tubules </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sperm cells are produced in the seminiferous tubules. The seminiferous tubules are located within the testes, and are the specific location of meiosis, and the subsequent creation of male gametes, i.e., sperm cells.</div>", "topic": "REPRODUCTION : REPRODUCTION IN MAMMALS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The male reproductive part of a flower is made up of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">anther and filament </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ovary and ovule </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ovule and style </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stigma and filament </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The male reproductive part of a flower is made up of anther and filament, collectively known as the stamen. The anther is the part of the stamen where pollen is produced, and the filament is the stalk that holds the anther.</div>", "topic": "REPRODUCTION : SEXUAL REPRODUCTION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following factors will most likely lead to overcrowding within a population? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Absence of predators </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Emigration </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Food shortage </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Absence of territorial behaviour </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Overcrowding within a population is most likely to occur in the absence of predators. Predators help control the population size by preying on the species. If predators are absent, the population can grow unchecked, leading to overcrowding. Emigration and food shortage would decrease a population, not increase it. Absence of territorial behaviour could potentially lead to overcrowding, but not as directly as the absence of predators.</div>", "topic": "THE ECOLOGY OF POPULATIONS : FACTORS AFFECTING POPULATION SIZES"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Population growth rate may be defined as the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mortality rate per unit area over a period </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">number of times an organism occurs within a given period </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">number of a particular species per unit area </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">net rate of natality and mortality in the habitat over a period. </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Population growth rate is defined as the net rate of natality (births) and mortality (deaths) in the habitat over a period. It is a measure of how the size of a population changes over time. The other options do not accurately define population growth rate. Mortality rate per unit area over a period, number of times an organism occurs within a given period, and number of a particular species per unit area are all measures of population density, not growth rate.</div>", "topic": "THE ECOLOGY OF POPULATIONS : POPULATION DENSITY AND OVERCROWDING"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The longest bone in the body is the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">humerus </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">femur </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">scapula </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tibia </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The femur, or thigh bone, is the longest bone in the human body. It extends from the hip to the knee. The other options, humerus, scapula, and tibia, are not the longest bones in the body.</div>", "topic": "SUPPORT AND MOVEMENT : TYPES AND FUNCTIONS OF THE SKELETON"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following structures is not a skeletal material? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Chitin </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cartilage </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bone </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Muscle </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Skeletal materials are hard structures that provide support and protection to the body. Examples include bone, cartilage, and chitin. Muscle, on the other hand, is a soft tissue that is responsible for producing force and motion. Therefore, muscle is not a skeletal material.</div>", "topic": "SUPPORT AND MOVEMENT : SUPPORTING TISSUES IN ANIMALS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following pairs of organisms are photosynthetic? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amoeba and Paramecium </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Volvox and Rhizopus </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Chlamydomonas and Euglena </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nostoc and Plasmodium </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Photosynthesis is a process used by plants and other organisms to convert light energy into chemical energy that can later be released to fuel the organisms' activities. Chlamydomonas and Euglena are both unicellular green algae that have chloroplasts and can perform photosynthesis. The other pairs listed either do not have the capability to perform photosynthesis or are not both photosynthetic.</div>", "topic": "NUTRITION : PHOTOSYNTHESIS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Why are viruses sometimes classified as living things?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They can move independently</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They can respire without a host</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They reproduce only inside host cells</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They contain chlorophyll for photosynthesis</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Viruses display living characteristics only when inside a host cell, where they use the host's machinery to make copies of themselves. Outside a host, they are inert and do not carry out processes like respiration or movement. They do not contain chlorophyll and cannot photosynthesize.</div>", "topic": "LIVING ORGANISMS : CHARACTERISTICS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An old man is likely to be long-sighted because age affects the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">optic nerves </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">retina </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ciliary muscles </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cornea </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Long-sightedness, or hypermetropia, is a common eye condition that causes nearby objects to appear blurred, while distant objects can be seen clearly. This condition is often age-related and is caused by the loss of elasticity of the ciliary muscles in the eye. As we age, the lens of the eye becomes less flexible, making it harder to focus on close objects, hence the correct answer is 'ciliary muscles'.</div>", "topic": "COORDINATION AND CONTROL : THE SENSE ORGANS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In mammals, stimulus is transferred from the receptor muscles to the central nervous system through the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">motor neurons </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">effector muscles </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dendrites </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sensory neurons </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the nervous system, sensory neurons play a crucial role in carrying information from sensory receptors (like touch or heat receptors in the skin) to the central nervous system (brain and spinal cord). This is how the body communicates sensory information to the brain for processing. Therefore, the correct answer is 'sensory neurons'.</div>", "topic": "COORDINATION AND CONTROL : NERVOUS COORDINATION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following structures functions as an excretory, system found in flatworm? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Contractile vacuole </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nephridium </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Flame cell </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Malpighian tubule </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Flatworms, or Platyhelminthes, have a specialized excretory system for the removal of waste products from the body. This system is composed of a network of tubules connected to flame cells (also known as protonephridia). These flame cells function like a kidney, removing waste materials from the body, hence the correct answer is 'Flame cell'.</div>", "topic": "EXCRETION : EXCRETORY MECHANISMS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In evolution, analogous structures are significant because they show </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">physiological diversity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">functional diversity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">genetic diversity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">structural diversity </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Analogous structures in evolution are significant because they show functional diversity. These are structures in different species having the same function but have evolved separately, thus do not share common ancestor. They are a result of convergent evolution and demonstrate how different species can develop similar traits due to similar environmental challenges, despite not being closely related.</div>", "topic": "EVOLUTION : EVIDENCE OF EVOLUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following actions supports conservation? To </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">protect endangered species </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">preserve trees for timber </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">permit hunting activities </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">provide income for the government </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Conservation supports the protection of endangered species. This involves implementing measures to prevent the extinction of species, preserving their habitats, and promoting biodiversity. The other options do not directly support conservation. Preserving trees for timber and permitting hunting activities can lead to deforestation and loss of biodiversity, while providing income for the government is not directly related to conservation.</div>", "topic": "HUMANS AND ENVIRONMENT : CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The process of anaerobic respiration of yeast in sugar solution is known as </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oxidation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fermentation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tissue respiration </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">alcohol production </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The process of anaerobic respiration of yeast in sugar solution is known as fermentation. In the absence of oxygen, yeast cells can convert sugar into alcohol and carbon dioxide through the process of fermentation. This is different from oxidation, which requires oxygen, and tissue respiration, which is the process of cells in a tissue using oxygen to produce energy. Alcohol production is a result of the fermentation process, not the process itself.</div>", "topic": "RESPIRATION : ANAEROBIC RESPIRATION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The gradual disappearance of certain traits from a population over generations is mainly due to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">natural selection</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">variation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adaptation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mutation </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Natural selection is the process by which individuals with traits that are less suited to the environment are less likely to survive and reproduce. Over generations, these traits become less common or disappear entirely from the population. Adaptation refers to the traits that help organisms survive, mutation introduces new traits, and variation is the presence of differences within a population.</div>", "topic": "VARIATION IN POPULATION : APPLICATION OF VARIATION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The role of dead organic matter in the soil is to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make the soil black </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase the mineral salt content </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">provide food for all living organisms </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">increase the acidity of soil </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The role of dead organic matter in the soil is to increase the mineral salt content. Dead organic matter, also known as humus, decomposes into the soil, releasing nutrients and mineral salts that are essential for plant growth. While it can also provide food for some organisms and affect the soil's color and acidity, its primary role is to enrich the soil with nutrients.</div>", "topic": "SOIL : SOIL FERTILITY"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which factor is important in aquatic environments but generally irrelevant in dry land ecosystems?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Temperature </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sunlight </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Humidity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Water cloudiness</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Water cloudiness, also called turbidity, measures the amount of suspended particles in water. It is a critical factor in aquatic habitats because it affects light penetration and water quality, but it is not a relevant environmental factor in terrestrial (land) habitats. Temperature, sunlight, and humidity are all significant in terrestrial ecosystems.</div>", "topic": "NATURAL HABITAT : AQUATIC TERRESTRIAL AND ARBOREAL"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following parts of the skeleton does not have a protective function? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ribs </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Carpals </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Skull </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pelvis </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Carpals, also known as the wrist bones, do not have a protective function. The Ribs protect the heart and lungs, the Skull protects the brain, and the Pelvis protects the internal reproductive organs and the lower part of the digestive system.</div>", "topic": "SUPPORT AND MOVEMENT : TYPES AND FUNCTIONS OF THE SKELETON"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which type of teeth in humans is used mainly for tearing food?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Molars</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Canines</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Premolars</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Incisors</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Canines are pointed teeth in humans that are specialized for tearing and holding food, especially meat. Molars are used for grinding food, premolars for crushing, and incisors for cutting. This specialization of teeth helps humans chew and digest food effectively.</div>", "topic": "LOCAL(NIGERIAN) BIOMES : TROPICAL RAINFOREST"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following organisms has a symbiotic relationship with green algae? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amoeba </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paramecium </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hydra </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Euglena </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hydra has a symbiotic relationship with green algae. The algae live in the cells of the hydra and perform photosynthesis, providing the hydra with nutrients. In return, the hydra provides the algae with protection and access to light. Hydra, a small freshwater animal, lives in a symbiotic relationship with algae called Chlorella that it carries inside its cells. </div>", "topic": "ECOLOGY : SYMBIOTIC INTERACTIONS OF PLANTS AND ANIMALS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statements below are about evolution of species  <br/> I. Members of a species vary <br/>  ll. Organisms produce many offspring  <br/> lll. The mechanism of evolution is inheritance of acquired characters  <br/> IV. Changes in the phenotype is brought about by the individual itself  <br/> Which of the statement(s) is/are related to the Darwin's theory of evolution? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">I only </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">II only </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">I, II and IV </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">II and IV only </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Darwin's theory of evolution is based on the principles of variation and natural selection. The first statement, 'Members of a species vary', refers to the principle of variation, which states that individuals within a species have different characteristics. The second statement, 'Organisms produce many offspring', refers to the principle of overproduction, which states that species produce more offspring than can survive, leading to competition for resources. The third and fourth statements are not part of Darwin's theory. They refer to the theory of Lamarck, which proposed that characteristics acquired or lost during an organism's lifetime are inherited by its offspring, a concept that has been largely discredited.</div>", "topic": "EVOLUTION : THEORIES OF EVOLUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Primary growth in plants is brought about by the activity of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">meristem </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">endodermis </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">epidermis </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mesophyll </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Primary growth in plants, which results in elongation of the plant body, is brought about by the activity of the meristem. Meristematic cells are undifferentiated or partially differentiated cells that can divide and produce new cells. They are responsible for the growth and development of plants. The other options - endodermis, epidermis, and mesophyll - are specific types of plant tissues, but they do not contribute to primary growth.</div>", "topic": "GROWTH : MEANING OF GROWTH"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following fields of study may not yield strong evidence of evolution? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fossil </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Histology </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ecology </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Genetics </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Histology, the study of the microscopic structure of tissues, may not yield strong evidence of evolution. While it can provide information about the structure and function of tissues in different organisms, it does not directly provide evidence of evolutionary relationships or changes over time. On the other hand, fossils, ecology, and genetics can provide strong evidence of evolution. Fossils show the existence of extinct species and changes in species over time. Ecology can show how species adapt to their environments, which can provide evidence of natural selection. Genetics can show how traits are passed from generation to generation and how they change over time, which can provide evidence of evolution.</div>", "topic": "EVOLUTION : EVIDENCE OF EVOLUTION"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following factors does not affect the distribution of organisms in an aquatic habitat? </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Availability of nutrient  <br/> </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Depth of water </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Humidity </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Temperature </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Humidity does not affect the distribution of organisms in an aquatic habitat. Humidity refers to the amount of water vapor in the air and is a factor that affects terrestrial habitats more than aquatic ones. In aquatic habitats, factors such as availability of nutrients, depth of water, and temperature play a significant role in the distribution of organisms.</div>", "topic": "ECOLOGY : FACTORS AFFECTING THE DISTRIBUTION OF ORGANISMS"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lateral meristem in flowering plants is found in the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cortex </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pericycle </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cambium </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pith </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lateral meristem in flowering plants is found in the cambium. The cambium is a type of tissue found in plants and is responsible for secondary growth that makes the stem or root increase in diameter and thickness. The other options, cortex, pericycle, and pith, are not where lateral meristem is found.</div>", "topic": "INTERNAL STRUCTURE OF A FLOWERING PLANT : STEM"}, {"id": "objective>Biology>2020-Model-II>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> A hormone secreted at IV serves to?   </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make the body react to emergencies <br/> </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lower blood glucose level <br/> </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">raise the level of calcium ions in the blood <br/> </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">facilitate the development of facial hairs <br/> </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">IV is the Gonads .Gonads are the sex organs and include the male testes and female ovaries. Their main role is the production of steroid hormones. The testes produce androgens, which allow for the development of secondary sex characteristics and the production of sperm cells. Testosterone, the most prominent androgen in males, stimulates the development and functioning of the primary sex organs. It also stimulates the development and maintenance of secondary male characteristics, such as hair growth on the face and the deep pitch of the voice <br/> </div>", "topic": "COORDINATION AND CONTROL : HORMONAL CONTROL"}];
